Hall of the Five Hundred (Palazzo Vecchio, Florence)|https://www.florenceinferno.com/hall-of-the-five-hundred/|dei Cinquecento) is the largest and most important room in terms of artistic and  ...    This impressive hall, which plays a key role in Dan Brown’s Inferno, is 54 meters long, 23 meters wide, and  ...    The room is on the first floor of the building and part of the wing of the palace built in the fifteenth century, adjacent to the oldest section built by Arnolfo di Cambio. The Hall of the Five Hundred was built in 1494 by Simone del Pollaiuolo and Francesco Domenico and commissioned by Fra Girolamo Savonarola. Savonarola had ousted the Medici from power for a short period and had founded a new Florentine Republic, which lasted between 1494 and 1498. He tried to establish a more democratic government for the city of Florence and thus created the Council of Five Hundred (or Great Council), consisting of five hundred people, modeled after the Grand Council of Venice.  ...    The tangible result of these reforms was the creation of the Salone dei Cinquecento in the government building,
