Cosimo I de' Medici: Politics, Portraiture, and Propaganda|https://scholarworks.arcadia.edu/showcase/2024/arts/1/|A ruler’s image was an essential part of Italian Renaissance culture, particularly in the realm of the princely court.  ...    highlighting the aspirational ideals of the time. It is thought that the Florentine senate ratified Cosimo I de’ Medici’s election because they believed him to be weak and easily manipulated. Precisely because his election was so  ...    employed visual imagery to deflect and neutralize challenges to his authority and looked to family precedents to give a sense of continuity and legitimacy to his regime. Through an analysis of Bronzino's Portrait of Duke Cosimo I de Medici as Orpheus and Cosimo I de Medici in Armor, as well as Benvenuto Cellini's Cosimo I de' Medici bronze portrait bust, this thesis seeks to show that Cosimo promoted his authority, legitimacy, and the Medici name itself by propagating idealized images that obscured the nature of Cosimo’s transition to power, and instead focused on his role in ushering  ...    Kopf, Emilie, "Cosimo I de'
